'''One-banana problem''' is a humorous phrase used sporadically to provide a context of difficulty or importance to workplace tasks.

An example of this phrase stems from larger technical worksites, where computer systems have dedicated operators for routine administrative tasks. Programmers and hardware people at these sites may look down on such operators and claim that a trained [[monkey]] could do their job. 

It is frequently observed that the incentives that would be offered to said monkeys can be used as a scale to describe the difficulty of a task. A one-[[banana]] problem is simple; hence, "It's only a one-banana job at the most; what's taking them so long?" At [[IBM]], folklore divides the world into one-, two-, and three-banana problems.

Other cultures have different hierarchies and may divide them more finely; at [[International Computers Ltd|ICL]], for example, five [[grape]]s (a bunch) equals a banana. Their upper limit for the in-house ''sysapes'' is said to be two bananas and three grapes (another source claims it's three bananas and one grape, but observes &quot;However, this is subject to local variations, [[cosmic ray]]s and [[ISO]]&quot;). At a complication level any higher than that, one asks the manufacturers to send someone around to check things.

